─────────────────────────────────────────
DIMENSION 1: BUSINESS QUALITY (0–100)
─────────────────────────────────────────
This dimension assesses the structural quality of the business model — the durability of margins,
the evidence of pricing power, and the consistency of revenue growth over time.

Analytical framework:
  → Gross margin: absolute level vs. sector norms, and multi-year trend (expanding/stable/contracting)
  → Operating leverage: does revenue growth translate to disproportionate EBIT growth?
  → Revenue growth: multi-year CAGR, not just YoY; is growth consistent year-over-year or lumpy?
  → Net income growing faster than revenue = margin expansion = pricing power evidence
  → Compare gross margin trend to revenue growth trend: divergence is a red flag

Scoring calibration:
  91–100  Rare — gross margin 70%+, consistent 20%+ revenue CAGR, clear margin expansion,
          visible pricing power (NI growing meaningfully faster than revenue)
  76–90   Excellent — gross margin 50–70%, consistent 12–20% CAGR, stable/expanding margins
  61–75   Good — gross margin 30–50%, consistent 8–12% CAGR, broadly stable margins
  41–60   Average — gross margin 20–30%, moderate growth (3–8%), mixed margin trend
  21–40   Below average — gross margin < 20%, slow/declining growth, margin pressure
  0–20    Structurally challenged — negative margins, revenue declining, or commoditised

─────────────────────────────────────────
DIMENSION 2: UNIT ECONOMICS & CASH GENERATION (0–100)
─────────────────────────────────────────
This dimension assesses whether the reported earnings are backed by real cash generation —
the hallmark of a capital-light compounder vs. an accrual-heavy business.

Analytical framework:
  → FCF/Net Income ratio: the single most important check — < 0.7x raises serious concerns
  → FCF yield: free cash flow as % of market cap — is the business cheap on a cash basis?
  → Capex/Revenue: < 5% = asset-light; 5–10% = moderate; > 15% = capital-intensive
  → Is FCF growing faster than revenue? (leverage on the P&L flowing through to cash)
  → Operating cash flow vs. net income divergence signals accrual risk

Scoring calibration:
  91–100  Exceptional — FCF/NI > 1.1x, FCF yield > 7%, capex/rev < 5%, FCF growing > revenue
  76–90   Strong — FCF/NI > 0.9x, FCF yield > 5%, low capex, clean cash conversion
  61–75   Good — FCF/NI > 0.75x, FCF yield > 3%, manageable capex
  41–60   Average — FCF/NI 0.5–0.75x, FCF yield 1–3%, moderate capex
  21–40   Weak — FCF below NI, high capex, or FCF yield < 1%
  0–20    Poor — negative FCF, FCF/NI < 0.5x, or data entirely missing

─────────────────────────────────────────
DIMENSION 3: RETURNS ON CAPITAL (0–100)
─────────────────────────────────────────
ROIC is the single most predictive metric of long-term value creation. A business that earns
25% ROIC consistently will compound intrinsic value at that rate regardless of valuation starting point.

Analytical framework:
  → ROIC level: compare to estimated WACC (assume 8–10% for most businesses)
  → ROIC trend: improving suggests moat widening; declining suggests competitive erosion
  → ROIC consistency: volatile ROIC signals cyclicality or execution risk
  → ROE cross-check: if ROE >> ROIC, leverage is driving returns (not economic quality)
  → Marginal ROIC: for growing companies, is the incremental capital deployed at high returns?

Scoring calibration:
  91–100  Exceptional — ROIC > 30% sustained, improving trend, clearly above cost of capital
  76–90   Excellent — ROIC 20–30%, stable or improving, strong spread over WACC
  61–75   Good — ROIC 12–20%, stable, meaningful spread over WACC
  41–60   Average — ROIC 7–12%, minimal spread over WACC
  21–40   Below average — ROIC 3–7%, close to cost of capital, limited value creation
  0–20    Value-destroying — ROIC < 3%, negative, or no data

─────────────────────────────────────────
DIMENSION 4: GROWTH QUALITY & COMPOUNDING TRACK RECORD (0–100)
─────────────────────────────────────────
THIS IS THE MOST CRITICAL DIMENSION FOR IDENTIFYING GENUINE COMPOUNDERS.

A consistent 15% grower for 5 years is worth far more than a 30% one-year grower followed by
declines. Consistency of growth is the primary differentiator between compounders and mediocre businesses.

Analytical framework:
  → Revenue multi-year CAGR: compute across the full available historical period
  → Net income multi-year CAGR: compare to revenue CAGR — NI CAGR > Rev CAGR = margin expansion
  → Growth consistency: compute year-over-year growth rates for each year and assess variance
    Low variance (all years within ±5pp of the mean) = high quality
    High variance (years ranging from -10% to +40%) = low quality, lumpy, or cyclical
  → Growth trajectory: is the most recent growth rate above or below the historical average?
    Accelerating = positive signal; decelerating = scrutinise carefully
  → Down years: any year with negative revenue growth is a significant penalty
  → Organic vs. inorganic: if growth is acquisition-driven, ROIC may be masking the truth

Scoring calibration:
  91–100  Elite compounder — Revenue CAGR 20%+, NI CAGR > Rev CAGR, near-zero variance,
          no down years, growth accelerating or stable
  76–90   Excellent — Revenue CAGR 12–20%, NI CAGR > Rev CAGR, low variance, no down years
  61–75   Good — Revenue CAGR 8–12%, positive NI expansion, moderate consistency
  41–60   Average — Revenue CAGR 4–8%, NI roughly in line, some year-to-year variation
  21–40   Below average — Revenue CAGR < 4%, or significant variance, or 1–2 down years
  0–20    Declining or erratic — revenue shrinking overall, multiple down years, or highly volatile

─────────────────────────────────────────
DIMENSION 5: BALANCE SHEET STRENGTH (0–100)
─────────────────────────────────────────
A strong balance sheet is optionality — it enables counter-cyclical investment, buybacks at lows,
and bolt-on acquisitions. A leveraged balance sheet is a constraint.

Analytical framework:
  → Net debt position: net cash (negative net debt) is the gold standard
  → Net Debt/EBITDA: primary leverage metric
  → Interest coverage: EBIT / interest expense (> 10x = comfortable; < 3x = concerning)
  → Balance sheet trajectory: is leverage increasing or decreasing over time?
  → Goodwill as % of total assets: > 50% signals acquisition risk and intangible-heavy balance sheet

Scoring calibration:
  91–100  Fortress — net cash position, zero leverage, financial optionality fully open
  76–90   Strong — low leverage (< 0.5x ND/EBITDA), substantial financial flexibility
  61–75   Good — moderate leverage (0.5–1.5x), comfortable coverage, no near-term concerns
  41–60   Adequate — leverage 1.5–2.5x, manageable but limits strategic flexibility
  21–40   Stretched — leverage 2.5–4x, or goodwill-heavy, or declining coverage
  0–20    Distressed — leverage > 4x, or covenant risk, or negative equity signals

─────────────────────────────────────────
DIMENSION 6: PHOENICIAN CAPITAL FIT (0–100)
─────────────────────────────────────────
Holistic qualitative judgment integrating all five dimensions above with Phoenician's specific mandate.
This is your overall assessment as a senior analyst — does this company deserve further research?

Analytical framework:
  → Owner/founder alignment: company age, CEO tenure, ownership structure, insider buying history
  → Moat durability: how sustainable are the high returns? Is the competitive position widening?
  → Business model scalability: can this grow 5–10x without proportional capital reinvestment?
  → Information edge: is this genuinely under-followed? ($250M–$2B market cap, limited analyst coverage)
  → Valuation context: given growth rate and ROIC, is current valuation attractive, fair, or stretched?
    (A 20x EV/EBIT for a 20% ROIC, 15% compounder is CHEAP. A 10x EV/EBIT for a 6% ROIC grower is EXPENSIVE.)
  → Portfolio fit: does this complement Phoenician's existing holdings in geography, sector, and style?
  → Red flags: any accounting concerns, governance issues, key-person risk, customer concentration?

Scoring calibration:
  91–100  Exceptional — must investigate immediately; rare business with all criteria firing
  76–90   High conviction — strong compounder candidate, one or two manageable concerns
  61–75   Interesting — quality business, worth deeper research, some gaps to address
  41–60   Marginal — some interesting attributes, but insufficient differentiation for Phoenician
  21–40   Weak fit — does not meet Phoenician's quality or growth standards
  0–20    No fit — fundamentally incompatible with mandate

